Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.630 --> 00:00:07.367
Prof: So you remember
Pasteur was very fond of racemic

00:00:07.367 --> 00:00:09.280
and tartaric acid.
 

00:00:09.280 --> 00:00:13.052
So when he'd travel around he
would look for samples of

00:00:13.052 --> 00:00:14.170
tartaric acid.
 

00:00:14.170 --> 00:00:18.115
There are very detailed
accounts that he published of

00:00:18.115 --> 00:00:19.330
these travels.
 

00:00:19.330 --> 00:00:22.980
I haven't found this one,
so I'm not sure it's true.

00:00:22.980 --> 00:00:25.452
It may be apocryphal,
but it was told to me by the

00:00:25.452 --> 00:00:27.370
guy who taught me organic
chemistry.

00:00:27.370 --> 00:00:29.305
So I pass it onto you,
for what it's worth,

00:00:29.305 --> 00:00:30.780
because it makes a good point.
 

00:00:30.780 --> 00:00:34.220
He said that Pasteur was in
Alsace,

00:00:34.220 --> 00:00:37.310
the wine-producing region in
northeast France,

00:00:37.310 --> 00:00:41.495
and in the town of Thann he
found in a pharmacy a bottle of

00:00:41.495 --> 00:00:43.660
racemic acid that was moldy.
 

00:00:43.660 --> 00:00:47.200
So remember racemic acid's the
50:50 mixture.

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:50.985
So, since he liked racemic acid
-- and in fact it was becoming

00:00:50.985 --> 00:00:51.420
rare.
 

00:00:51.420 --> 00:00:53.480
It's a not a very common
product;

00:00:53.480 --> 00:00:55.240
mostly you get the handed stuff.
 

00:00:55.240 --> 00:01:00.442
So he took it back and cleaned
it up, got rid of the mold that

00:01:00.442 --> 00:01:02.149
was growing on it.
 

00:01:02.149 --> 00:01:06.132
And what he found was that
after he had purified it,

00:01:06.132 --> 00:01:09.022
it was the unnatural,
the left-handed,

00:01:09.022 --> 00:01:11.599
not the one you normally get.
 

00:01:11.599 --> 00:01:14.938
Can you see an explanation for
that?

00:01:14.938 --> 00:01:19.793
Had the apothecary mislabeled
it because he thought he could

00:01:19.793 --> 00:01:24.400
get a higher price for racemic
than for tartaric acid?

00:01:24.400 --> 00:01:27.010
Or might he have been innocent?
 

00:01:27.010 --> 00:01:27.819
Zack?
 

00:01:27.819 --> 00:01:28.879
Student:  Was it the
mold by any chance?

00:01:28.879 --> 00:01:30.989
Prof: What did the mold
do?

00:01:30.989 --> 00:01:32.590
Student:  Might have
converted one into all.

00:01:32.590 --> 00:01:34.830
Prof: Didn't convert.
 

00:01:34.830 --> 00:01:35.830
Student:  It didn't?
 

00:01:35.830 --> 00:01:38.534
Prof: The mold ate the
natural stuff,

00:01:38.534 --> 00:01:41.553
converted it into something
completely different,

00:01:41.553 --> 00:01:43.440
leaving the unnatural one.
 

00:01:43.440 --> 00:01:45.310
Okay?
 

00:01:45.310 --> 00:01:47.620
Remember the smell of the
carvones?

00:01:47.620 --> 00:01:49.358
Natural things,
enzymes and so on,

00:01:49.358 --> 00:01:51.519
can distinguish between the two
hands,

00:01:51.519 --> 00:01:54.736
and naturally the stuff that
normally eats tartaric acid is

00:01:54.736 --> 00:01:56.790
going to eat normal tartaric
acid,

00:01:56.790 --> 00:01:58.040
not the unusual one.
 

00:01:58.040 --> 00:01:59.670
So it left the unusual one.
 

00:01:59.670 --> 00:02:04.180
The penicillium glaucum
had eaten the R,R.

00:02:04.180 --> 00:02:08.218
Okay, so that's one way of
doing resolution,

00:02:08.218 --> 00:02:11.979
to get rid of one enantiomer
from a racemic mixture,

00:02:11.979 --> 00:02:15.157
leaving the other one,
because diastereomeric

00:02:15.157 --> 00:02:17.538
reactions have different rates.
 

00:02:17.538 --> 00:02:20.476
It's a right hand shaking a
right hand versus a right hand

00:02:20.476 --> 00:02:22.030
shaking a left hand;
they're just different.

00:02:22.030 --> 00:02:24.280
So one will go faster than the
other.

00:02:24.280 --> 00:02:28.400
So if you react a racemate with
some chiral reagent --

00:02:28.400 --> 00:02:31.084
of course you have to use only
one hand of that other thing you

00:02:31.084 --> 00:02:33.295
add in there --
but then you'll react with one

00:02:33.295 --> 00:02:34.330
more than the other.
 

00:02:34.330 --> 00:02:37.509
It could be even a catalyst so
that it doesn't get consumed;

00:02:37.509 --> 00:02:39.270
an enzyme, for example.
 

00:02:39.270 --> 00:02:42.407
But that's not Nature's way,
because it's very inefficient

00:02:42.407 --> 00:02:44.389
to make both and then destroy
one.

00:02:44.389 --> 00:02:48.318
What nature does is prepare
only one enantiomer.

00:02:48.318 --> 00:02:50.414
And you can do that,
prepare only one,

00:02:50.414 --> 00:02:53.190
by starting with something
that's already a single

00:02:53.190 --> 00:02:55.229
enantiomer and building on that.
 

00:02:55.229 --> 00:02:58.900
Or you can use a reagent,
which is resolved,

00:02:58.900 --> 00:03:02.009
that will -- because
diastereomeric rates are

00:03:02.009 --> 00:03:05.622
different --
will tend to produce one of the

00:03:05.622 --> 00:03:07.060
two enantiomers.
 

00:03:07.060 --> 00:03:10.788
So here's an example of this
molecule we've been talking

00:03:10.788 --> 00:03:13.498
about,
Eisai-7389, with its nineteen

00:03:13.498 --> 00:03:16.622
asymmetric centers,
that's made artificially,

00:03:16.622 --> 00:03:17.520
commercially.
 

00:03:17.520 --> 00:03:21.068
And this is where those
nineteen centers came from.

00:03:21.068 --> 00:03:24.878
Five of them came from starting
materials that they bought as a

00:03:24.878 --> 00:03:25.740
single hand.
 

00:03:25.740 --> 00:03:27.770
But the rest were all made.
 

00:03:27.770 --> 00:03:30.348
One of them was done by
chromatography.

00:03:30.348 --> 00:03:33.888
They have chromatography
columns about this big around,

00:03:33.888 --> 00:03:36.639
and this high,
with chiral stuff inside.

00:03:36.639 --> 00:03:38.500
So you pass your thing through.
 

00:03:38.500 --> 00:03:41.541
One hand goes through a little
faster than the other,

00:03:41.541 --> 00:03:45.110
because of its diastereomeric
interaction with the packing;

00:03:45.110 --> 00:03:46.508
one comes through quicker.
 

00:03:46.508 --> 00:03:48.930
And they actually do that for
one of the centers.

00:03:48.930 --> 00:03:52.541
But the others are all done by
reactions that preferentially

00:03:52.541 --> 00:03:54.990
give one center rather than the
other.

00:03:54.990 --> 00:03:58.324
Three of them are ones that
everybody knew which one they

00:03:58.324 --> 00:03:59.098
would give.
 

00:03:59.098 --> 00:04:02.270
The other ones they just had to
hope, and fiddle around with

00:04:02.270 --> 00:04:05.331
different reactions until they
found one that would do the

00:04:05.331 --> 00:04:05.870
trick.
 

00:04:05.870 --> 00:04:09.074
So anyhow, they were able to
generate these nineteen

00:04:09.074 --> 00:04:10.080
stereocenters.
 

00:04:10.080 --> 00:04:13.348
Now we're left with a problem.
 

00:04:13.348 --> 00:04:17.089
That incidentally is all we're
going to have for the exam on

00:04:17.089 --> 00:04:17.660
Friday.
 

00:04:17.660 --> 00:04:18.259
Okay?
 

00:04:18.259 --> 00:04:20.980
So now we're on to other stuff
that will be covered on the

00:04:20.980 --> 00:04:23.750
final exam, and in particular
return to this question about

00:04:23.750 --> 00:04:24.850
the tartaric acids.
 

00:04:24.850 --> 00:04:28.439
Remember there's d-(+)
and l-(-).

00:04:28.439 --> 00:04:31.978
Could you have l-(+) and
d-(-),

00:04:31.978 --> 00:04:34.069
of a different compound?
 

00:04:34.069 --> 00:04:36.629
Why not?
 

00:04:36.629 --> 00:04:40.220
What does d or l
mean, in this context?

00:04:40.220 --> 00:04:44.790
Student:
&gt;.

00:04:44.790 --> 00:04:45.819
Prof: Andrew?
 

00:04:45.819 --> 00:04:47.680
Student:  It reflects
light to the left.

00:04:47.680 --> 00:04:49.600
Prof: It means which way
it rotates the light.

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:51.160
Right?
 

00:04:51.160 --> 00:04:53.790
And the plus means the same
thing, as d.

00:04:53.790 --> 00:04:56.670
So it's redundant,
this particular nomenclature.

00:04:56.670 --> 00:04:59.471
But there's a question mark
because when -- Fischer just

00:04:59.471 --> 00:05:00.490
guessed, remember?
 

00:05:00.490 --> 00:05:02.569
And it could easily have been
the opposite.

00:05:02.569 --> 00:05:04.120
So which way is it?
 

00:05:04.120 --> 00:05:05.129
Right?
 

00:05:05.129 --> 00:05:08.173
So if we knew,
if we knew how optical activity

00:05:08.173 --> 00:05:12.298
worked, then by measuring the
optical activity we'd know which

00:05:12.298 --> 00:05:14.529
of those structures is right.
 

00:05:14.529 --> 00:05:16.250
Okay?
 

00:05:16.250 --> 00:05:19.250
But we don't know that;
at least I don't know that.

00:05:19.250 --> 00:05:23.148
Now there's a lot of knowledge
about this, but it's a very,

00:05:23.148 --> 00:05:24.560
very tough problem.
 

00:05:24.560 --> 00:05:27.706
Fortunately there's a book by
Laurence Barron called

00:05:27.706 --> 00:05:31.036
Molecular Light Scattering
and Optical Activity,

00:05:31.036 --> 00:05:32.949
which goes into this stuff.
 

00:05:32.949 --> 00:05:35.949
And I see Professor Vaccaro --
Prof: I'm here.

00:05:35.949 --> 00:05:37.589
Prof: Oh,
so we have a copy of the book.

00:05:37.589 --> 00:05:38.540
That's great.
 

00:05:38.540 --> 00:05:42.910
But even better than that,
we have Laurence Barron.

00:05:42.910 --> 00:05:44.879
Prof: Or a copy of
Laurence Barron.

00:05:44.879 --> 00:05:46.100
Prof: Or a copy of
Laurence Barron.

