00:06:59.670 --> 00:07:03.817
So chirality then means,
as you well know,

00:07:03.817 --> 00:07:06.649
right- or left-handedness.
 

00:07:06.649 --> 00:07:09.810
It pervades much of modern
science;

00:07:09.810 --> 00:07:13.514
from the physics of elementary
particles, through organic

00:07:13.514 --> 00:07:16.490
stereochemistry,
to the structure and behavior

00:07:16.490 --> 00:07:20.819
of the molecules of life;
with a lot more besides.

00:07:20.819 --> 00:07:23.687
It comes up in what's called
nonlinear optics,

00:07:23.687 --> 00:07:26.709
involving intense lasers;
nanotechnology;

00:07:26.709 --> 00:07:28.250
materials, electrical
engineering;

00:07:28.250 --> 00:07:30.935
pharmaceuticals;
astrobiology;

00:07:30.935 --> 00:07:32.879
and origin of life.
 

00:07:32.879 --> 00:07:38.190
So it's a very important theme
in modern science.

00:07:38.190 --> 00:07:42.250
Now first of all though I'll
tell you a little bit about Lord

00:07:42.250 --> 00:07:42.860
Kelvin.
 

00:07:42.860 --> 00:07:45.776
He was the first person to
introduce the word

00:07:45.776 --> 00:07:47.899
chirality into science.
 

00:07:47.899 --> 00:07:52.608
He was professor of natural
philosophy in Glasgow -- which

00:07:52.608 --> 00:07:57.069
is my home university -- through
most of his career;

00:07:57.069 --> 00:07:58.459
well all of his career.
 

00:07:58.459 --> 00:08:01.906
He was one of the giants of
physics of the nineteenth

00:08:01.906 --> 00:08:02.569
century.
 

00:08:02.569 --> 00:08:08.586
He's best known for inventing
the absolute Kelvin temperature

00:08:08.586 --> 00:08:09.389
scale.
 

00:08:09.389 --> 00:08:13.134
Now he was originally,
his original name was William

00:08:13.134 --> 00:08:17.247
Thomson, but then he became
famous and became Sir William

00:08:17.247 --> 00:08:18.129
Thomson.
 

00:08:18.129 --> 00:08:22.209
Then he became even more
famous, so they made him a Lord.

00:08:22.209 --> 00:08:25.641
And when you're made a Lord in
the U.K., you choose your title

00:08:25.641 --> 00:08:28.793
from someplace that's dear to
your heart, maybe your home

00:08:28.793 --> 00:08:29.300
area.
 

00:08:29.300 --> 00:08:32.716
He took his title from the name
of the River Kelvin,

00:08:32.716 --> 00:08:36.200
which runs through the
University Park in Glasgow.

00:08:36.200 --> 00:08:39.450
So whenever you use the
absolute temperature scale now

00:08:39.450 --> 00:08:42.025
in the future,
you can picture this idyllic

00:08:42.025 --> 00:08:42.639
scene.
 

00:08:42.639 --> 00:08:45.868
Anyway, so he was the first to
introduce the word

00:08:45.868 --> 00:08:48.019
chirality into science.
 

00:08:48.019 --> 00:08:50.932
And here's his definition,
which you'll be familiar with:

00:08:50.932 --> 00:08:53.691
"I call any geometrical
figure or group of points

00:08:53.691 --> 00:08:56.466
chiral,
and say that it has chirality

00:08:56.466 --> 00:08:59.317
if its image in a plane mirror,
ideally realized,

00:08:59.317 --> 00:09:01.918
cannot be brought into
coincidence with itself."

00:09:01.918 --> 00:09:04.129
That was in his Baltimore
Lectures.

00:09:04.129 --> 00:09:07.743
So he's just emphasizing the
non-superimposabity of the

00:09:07.743 --> 00:09:10.419
mirror image,
the enantiomers of a chiral

00:09:10.419 --> 00:09:11.288
molecule.
 

00:09:11.288 --> 00:09:15.115
But of course the whole subject
started earlier with the

00:09:15.115 --> 00:09:19.957
wonderful work of Louis Pasteur,
who showed mirror-image chiral

00:09:19.957 --> 00:09:24.937
molecules show optical rotation
of equal magnitude but opposite

00:09:24.937 --> 00:09:28.080
sign;
which was an epoch-making

00:09:28.080 --> 00:09:29.178
discovery.
 

00:09:29.178 --> 00:09:32.999
So you've come across then
this, the fundamental

00:09:32.999 --> 00:09:37.062
manifestation of optical
activity, which is natural

00:09:37.062 --> 00:09:38.769
optical rotation.
 

00:09:38.769 --> 00:09:43.120
You put linearly polarized
light beam into a sample --

00:09:43.120 --> 00:09:47.840
say a sample of an isotropic
collection of chiral molecules,

00:09:47.840 --> 00:09:50.998
like a sugar solution -- and it
will come out the other side

00:09:50.998 --> 00:09:54.210
with the plane of polarization
rotated through some angle.

00:09:54.210 --> 00:09:56.681
And if you put in the mirror
image version,

00:09:56.681 --> 00:09:59.504
you'll get an equal but
opposite sense of optical

00:09:59.504 --> 00:10:00.269
rotation.
 

00:10:00.269 --> 00:10:04.336
Now it's not to be confused
with something called magnetic

00:10:04.336 --> 00:10:07.120
optical rotation,
the Faraday effect.

00:10:07.120 --> 00:10:08.788
I'm just mentioning this to you.
 

00:10:08.788 --> 00:10:12.120
You probably haven't come
across the Faraday effect yet,

00:10:12.120 --> 00:10:15.934
but you may do later on in your
studies, or in your professional

00:10:15.934 --> 00:10:16.480
life.
 

00:10:16.480 --> 00:10:18.418
So I'll mention the Faraday
effect.

00:10:18.418 --> 00:10:23.043
Faraday discovered,
in 1846, that achiral samples

00:10:23.043 --> 00:10:26.955
--
no natural optical activity

00:10:26.955 --> 00:10:30.221
there --
if you apply a static magnetic

00:10:30.221 --> 00:10:32.562
field,
parallel to the light beam,

00:10:32.562 --> 00:10:35.070
that will induce an optical
rotation.

00:10:35.070 --> 00:10:38.754
And if you put in -- if you
reverse the direction of the

00:10:38.754 --> 00:10:41.403
magnetic field,
relative to the light beam,

00:10:41.403 --> 00:10:43.967
you'll get an equal and
opposite sense of optical

00:10:43.967 --> 00:10:44.610
rotation.
 

00:10:44.610 --> 00:10:48.255
It would even work say for a
sample of water,

00:10:48.255 --> 00:10:49.500
for instance.
 

00:10:49.500 --> 00:10:52.418
Any material will show a
Faraday effect.

00:10:52.418 --> 00:10:56.640
But this has been a source of
much confusion,

00:10:56.640 --> 00:10:59.038
in fact, to scientists.
 

00:10:59.038 --> 00:11:02.500
Now Lord Kelvin was on the ball
here.

00:11:02.500 --> 00:11:03.549
He knew all about it.
 

00:11:03.549 --> 00:11:05.220
He made a statement here.
 

00:11:05.220 --> 00:11:07.764
He said, "The magnetic
rotation has neither

00:11:07.764 --> 00:11:10.200
right-handed nor left-handed
quality."

00:11:10.200 --> 00:11:14.336
(That is to say no chirality;
it's got nothing to do with

00:11:14.336 --> 00:11:15.139
chirality.)
 

00:11:15.139 --> 00:11:17.764
"This was perfectly
understood by Faraday and made

00:11:17.764 --> 00:11:21.042
clear in his writings,
yet even to the present day we

00:11:21.042 --> 00:11:24.548
frequently find the chiral
rotation and the magnetic

00:11:24.548 --> 00:11:28.399
rotation of the plane of
polarization classed together in

00:11:28.399 --> 00:11:32.592
a manner against which Faraday's
original description contains

00:11:32.592 --> 00:11:34.450
ample warning."
 

00:11:34.450 --> 00:11:37.590
Well Lord Kelvin would be
turning in his grave today,

00:11:37.590 --> 00:11:40.796
100 years later,
because you still see papers

00:11:40.796 --> 00:11:43.418
which involve the Faraday
effect,

00:11:43.418 --> 00:11:46.278
in some way or other,
and in the introduction they

00:11:46.278 --> 00:11:49.485
talk grandly of "inducing
chirality with a magnetic

00:11:49.485 --> 00:11:50.419
field."
 

00:11:50.419 --> 00:11:52.408
That is completely wrong.
 

00:11:52.408 --> 00:11:58.360
Just for the record -- probably
beyond your knowledge at the

00:11:58.360 --> 00:12:00.399
moment --
chiral phenomena,

00:12:00.399 --> 00:12:04.071
like natural optical rotation,
they're characterized by what's

00:12:04.071 --> 00:12:07.168
called time-even pseudoscalar
observables.

00:12:07.168 --> 00:12:12.075
A pseudoscalar is a number that
changes sign under reflection or

00:12:12.075 --> 00:12:14.919
inversion;
we'll leave it at that.

00:12:14.919 --> 00:12:16.668
So that's for the record.
 

00:12:16.668 --> 00:12:20.144
But well it turns out the
essential symmetry

00:12:20.144 --> 00:12:24.912
characteristics of natural and
magnetic optical rotation are

00:12:24.912 --> 00:12:29.033
completely different and you
need different sorts of

00:12:29.033 --> 00:12:33.100
molecular quantum states,
different characteristics to

00:12:33.100 --> 00:12:33.840
support them.
 

00:12:33.840 --> 00:12:36.110
But we won't pursue that.
 

00:12:36.110 --> 00:12:41.048
Right, now back to natural
optical rotation.

00:12:41.048 --> 00:12:46.720
So now we bring in circularly
polarized light.

00:12:46.720 --> 00:12:51.135
So in order to detect molecular
chirality, you must have some

00:12:51.135 --> 00:12:52.830
sort of chiral probe.
 

00:12:52.830 --> 00:12:58.360
Well what we're using here is
right and left-circularly

00:12:58.360 --> 00:13:00.820
polarized light beams.
 

00:13:00.820 --> 00:13:04.028
They are actually mirror-image
chiral systems.

00:13:04.028 --> 00:13:07.250
So they can be used as chiral
probes.

00:13:07.250 --> 00:13:12.065
So here's a representation of a
right-circularly polarized light

00:13:12.065 --> 00:13:12.600
beam.
 

00:13:12.600 --> 00:13:17.736
Now you know that light
involves electromagnetic

00:13:17.736 --> 00:13:22.870
oscillations in space,
and usually you just think of

00:13:22.870 --> 00:13:27.009
the oscillating electric vector
of a light wave,

00:13:27.009 --> 00:13:30.928
and if it's linearly polarized,
it's oscillating in one plane.

00:13:30.928 --> 00:13:34.333
There's actually also an
oscillating magnetic field

00:13:34.333 --> 00:13:38.080
vector that oscillates
perpendicular to the electric.

00:13:38.080 --> 00:13:39.570
We'll come back to that later.
 

00:13:39.570 --> 00:13:42.452
We're just looking at the
oscillating electric vector

00:13:42.452 --> 00:13:42.840
here.
 

00:13:42.840 --> 00:13:45.844
So if it's linearly polarized,
or plane polarized,

00:13:45.844 --> 00:13:47.990
it's just oscillating in a
plane;

00:13:47.990 --> 00:13:52.686
but circularly polarized light,
as well as an oscillation in

00:13:52.686 --> 00:13:54.038
this direction.
 

00:13:54.038 --> 00:13:59.304
You also have an electric
vector oscillating perpendicular

00:13:59.304 --> 00:14:01.798
but 90° out of phase.
 

00:14:01.798 --> 00:14:09.090
And what happens is you get
this circular polarization.

00:14:09.090 --> 00:14:11.899
Now this picture here,
this represents the

00:14:11.899 --> 00:14:16.220
instantaneous electric vectors
at different points in space,

00:14:16.220 --> 00:14:19.678
in the direction of
propagation, along the z

00:14:19.678 --> 00:14:20.509
direction.
 

00:14:20.509 --> 00:14:23.994
And so here we are,
that's just showing -- that's

00:14:23.994 --> 00:14:28.639
just connected the ends of the
instantaneous electric vectors.

00:14:28.639 --> 00:14:31.769
And there it is for
left-circularly polarized.

00:14:31.769 --> 00:14:35.817
Anyway, you can see that at the
very least those are chiral,

00:14:35.817 --> 00:14:38.836
those are helical,
and those are mirror-image

00:14:38.836 --> 00:14:40.139
chiral systems.
 

00:14:40.139 --> 00:14:43.038
Now here we go.
 

00:14:43.038 --> 00:14:46.787
This is some extra fancy stuff
that Professor McBride added to

00:14:46.787 --> 00:14:48.446
my &gt;
 

00:14:48.446 --> 00:14:49.428
presentation.
 

00:14:49.428 --> 00:14:52.710
He doesn't like -- it was too
simple and static.

00:14:52.710 --> 00:14:55.279
Anyway, so there we are.
 

00:14:55.279 --> 00:15:00.692
So now if you look at the wave,
if you just look at the

00:15:00.692 --> 00:15:04.500
electric vector through --
in a fixed plane,

00:15:04.500 --> 00:15:06.558
as the light wave is
propagating,

00:15:06.558 --> 00:15:10.883
there's the electric vector,
and it will rotate in the fixed

00:15:10.883 --> 00:15:11.470
plane.
 

00:15:11.470 --> 00:15:14.802
So rotating clockwise,
that defines right-circularly

00:15:14.802 --> 00:15:15.980
polarized light.
 

00:15:15.980 --> 00:15:23.899
And here we go,
rotating counter-clockwise;

00:15:23.899 --> 00:15:26.240
that's left-circularly
polarized light.

00:15:26.240 --> 00:15:30.599
Okay, so we now have a chiral
optical probe,

00:15:30.599 --> 00:15:33.538
circularly polarized light.
 

00:15:33.538 --> 00:15:37.192
Now chiral molecules respond
slightly differently to right

00:15:37.192 --> 00:15:39.629
and left-circularly polarized
light.

00:15:39.629 --> 00:15:45.320
I mean, an extreme example is
say in the world of engineering.

00:15:45.320 --> 00:15:51.298
You can't fit a left-handed nut
onto a right-handed bolt.

00:15:51.298 --> 00:15:58.019
That's an extreme example of
different chiral interactions.

00:15:58.019 --> 00:16:01.519
Well it's obviously much more
delicate than that here.

00:16:01.519 --> 00:16:05.235
But the point is right and
left-circularly polarized light

00:16:05.235 --> 00:16:08.755
interact just slightly
differently with a molecule of a

00:16:08.755 --> 00:16:10.058
given chirality.
 

00:16:10.058 --> 00:16:13.666
Anyway, there's a differential
absorption of right and

00:16:13.666 --> 00:16:15.980
left-circularly polarized light.
 

00:16:15.980 --> 00:16:19.057
That corresponds to a
phenomenon called circular

00:16:19.057 --> 00:16:22.527
dichroism, which is the basis of
a widely used form of

00:16:22.527 --> 00:16:25.668
spectroscopy used to study
chiral molecules.

00:16:25.668 --> 00:16:30.347
But now, what gives rise to
optical rotation is a difference

00:16:30.347 --> 00:16:34.947
in refractive index towards --
of right and left-circularly

00:16:34.947 --> 00:16:37.009
polarized light beams.
 

00:16:42.808 --> 00:16:46.195
Now linearly polarized light,
you can describe it as a

00:16:46.195 --> 00:16:50.027
coherent superposition of right
and left-circularly polarized

00:16:50.027 --> 00:16:51.879
waves of equal amplitude.
 

00:16:51.879 --> 00:16:54.928
Coherent means they're in-phase
with each other.

00:16:54.928 --> 00:16:58.962
Rather than being random,
they're oscillating in-phase

00:16:58.962 --> 00:17:01.778
with some fixed phase
relationship.

00:17:01.778 --> 00:17:06.384
So, for example,
now here's a linearly polarized

00:17:06.384 --> 00:17:07.660
light beam.
 

00:17:07.660 --> 00:17:12.895
But you can decompose it into a
superposition of a left-circular

00:17:12.895 --> 00:17:15.640
and a right-circular component.
 

00:17:15.640 --> 00:17:19.957
You see when those are at the
top they're reinforcing,

00:17:19.957 --> 00:17:24.355
and you've got the maximum
linearly polarized vector up

00:17:24.355 --> 00:17:25.088
here.
 

00:17:25.088 --> 00:17:27.287
As they come away,
left and right,

00:17:27.287 --> 00:17:31.548
they will tend to increasingly
cancel, and that will decrease.

00:17:31.548 --> 00:17:35.682
And when they're this way and
this way, you'll have zero

00:17:35.682 --> 00:17:39.892
electric field vector there,
and as you come down it will

00:17:39.892 --> 00:17:41.318
increase again.
 

00:17:41.318 --> 00:17:46.935
So you can decompose a linearly
polarized light into a coherent

00:17:46.935 --> 00:17:50.558
superposition of left and right
waves.

00:17:50.558 --> 00:17:57.789
Now, refractive index
corresponds to velocity through

00:17:57.789 --> 00:17:59.318
a medium.
 

00:17:59.318 --> 00:18:03.892
So if there's a difference in
refractive index for right and

00:18:03.892 --> 00:18:07.068
left-circularly polarized light
beams,

00:18:07.068 --> 00:18:10.085
that means there's a slight
difference in the velocity of

00:18:10.085 --> 00:18:13.101
the right and left-circularly
polarized light beams going

00:18:13.101 --> 00:18:14.338
through the medium.
 

00:18:14.338 --> 00:18:18.477
So the phase relations between
the two contrarotating electric

00:18:18.477 --> 00:18:19.970
vectors will change.
 

00:18:19.970 --> 00:18:23.678
And you can easily see,
this will give you a rotation

00:18:23.678 --> 00:18:25.890
in the plane of polarization.
 

00:18:25.890 --> 00:18:28.480
You see, if there's a
difference in velocity,

00:18:28.480 --> 00:18:32.078
then at some instant this
vector, this electric vectors of

00:18:32.078 --> 00:18:36.150
the left component will be here,
and the right component here.

00:18:36.150 --> 00:18:41.137
And if you take the resultant,
you see, it's no longer where

00:18:41.137 --> 00:18:41.900
it was.
 

00:18:41.900 --> 00:18:46.457
So this is a simple picture of
how optical rotation develops,

00:18:46.457 --> 00:18:50.406
in terms of different
refractive indices of the right

00:18:50.406 --> 00:18:52.230
and left components.
 

00:18:52.230 --> 00:18:55.982
Now there's a picture in
Atkins' Physical

00:18:55.982 --> 00:18:57.380
Chemistry.
 

00:18:57.380 --> 00:18:59.519
He tries to illustrate this
there.

00:18:59.519 --> 00:19:01.670
He's got the linearly polarized
beam coming through,

00:19:01.670 --> 00:19:04.959
and you've got the -- he's
broken it down into the left and

00:19:04.959 --> 00:19:06.907
right,
and he's saying the two

00:19:06.907 --> 00:19:09.160
velocities are slightly
different,

00:19:09.160 --> 00:19:12.000
and that gives you the
resultant optical rotation.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:15.978
You can easily develop an
expression for the angle of

00:19:15.978 --> 00:19:20.644
rotation as a function of the
difference in refractive indices

00:19:20.644 --> 00:19:24.930
for left and right-circularly
polarized light beams.

00:19:24.930 --> 00:19:27.288
And it's also -- it's a
function of the path length.

00:19:27.288 --> 00:19:31.625
Obviously the longer the path
length, the more rotation will

00:19:31.625 --> 00:19:32.358
develop.
 

00:19:32.358 --> 00:19:37.000
And there's the wavelength
there in the denominator.

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:39.390
In fact, I mean,
this is the secret;

00:19:39.390 --> 00:19:41.861
this path length,
that's the secret of how you

00:19:41.861 --> 00:19:43.400
get a measurable rotation.
 

00:19:43.400 --> 00:19:46.130
Because this is an incredibly
tiny effect.

00:19:46.130 --> 00:19:49.123
If it was just a single
molecule event you're looking

00:19:49.123 --> 00:19:52.288
at, the polarization changes,
you wouldn't see anything,

00:19:52.288 --> 00:19:53.440
they're so tiny.
 

00:19:53.440 --> 00:19:57.615
But you can build up this
rotation over long path lengths,

00:19:57.615 --> 00:19:59.740
centimeters or even meters.
 

00:19:59.740 --> 00:20:05.980
In fact, if you go to Google,
Google Images,

00:20:05.980 --> 00:20:09.747
and just Google 'circularly
polarized light,' you'll find

00:20:09.747 --> 00:20:13.380
lots of sites there which
describe polarized light,

00:20:13.380 --> 00:20:16.160
and they provide beautiful
simulations,

00:20:16.160 --> 00:20:20.640
animations of this effect here.
 

00:20:20.640 --> 00:20:24.582
I didn't want to download any
and try and show them here,

00:20:24.582 --> 00:20:27.538
but I would encourage you to go
to that.

00:20:27.538 --> 00:20:31.737
But go and look in particular
at this site here,

00:20:31.737 --> 00:20:32.720
enzim.hu.
 

00:20:32.720 --> 00:20:37.250
That comes from an institute of
enzymology in Budapest.

00:20:37.250 --> 00:20:41.105
They've got some beautiful
simulations of this optical

00:20:41.105 --> 00:20:45.690
rotation process and other more
exotic polarization effects,

00:20:45.690 --> 00:20:48.690
as light propagates through
matter.

00:20:48.690 --> 00:20:54.559
Now, let's try and -- so that's
just, what would you say,

00:20:54.559 --> 00:20:58.019
a phenomenological description.
 

00:20:58.019 --> 00:21:01.929
And in fact that's where most
physical chemistry textbooks

00:21:01.929 --> 00:21:02.410
stop.
 

00:21:02.410 --> 00:21:05.222
And in fact Atkins' Physical
Chemistry stops at that

00:21:05.222 --> 00:21:07.959
point,
and then just there's just sort

00:21:07.959 --> 00:21:11.578
of hand waving saying okay,
right and left-circularly

00:21:11.578 --> 00:21:14.752
polarized light interacts
slightly differently with the

00:21:14.752 --> 00:21:17.318
chiral molecule;
and they leave it at that.

00:21:17.318 --> 00:21:20.962
They don't attempt to try and
give you a picture in molecular

00:21:20.962 --> 00:21:21.509
detail.
 

00:21:21.509 --> 00:21:26.180
But Professor McBride wanted me
to try and attempt this.

00:21:26.180 --> 00:21:29.971
So just as a start,
this is a simple picture,

00:21:29.971 --> 00:21:34.279
a simple scattering picture of
optical rotation.

00:21:34.279 --> 00:21:39.075
Now a circularly polarized
light wave 'bouncing' from one

00:21:39.075 --> 00:21:43.125
group to the other,
as it scatters from a simple

00:21:43.125 --> 00:21:47.269
two-group chiral structure,
will sample the chirality.

00:21:47.269 --> 00:21:50.923
So here we have a simple
two-group chiral molecular

00:21:50.923 --> 00:21:51.798
structure.
 

00:21:51.798 --> 00:21:54.824
So we've got two achiral
groups, held in a rigid,

00:21:54.824 --> 00:21:56.210
twisted arrangement.
 

00:21:56.210 --> 00:21:59.078
I think that's left-handed I've
got there.

00:21:59.078 --> 00:22:02.212
And you can break down -- if
you look at most chiral

00:22:02.212 --> 00:22:05.777
molecules, just look at the
bonds, you can often break them

00:22:05.777 --> 00:22:06.328
down.
 

00:22:06.328 --> 00:22:12.078
You can see these sorts of
two-group structures throughout.

00:22:12.078 --> 00:22:18.549
Anyway, so a particular model
of optical rotation is that the

00:22:18.549 --> 00:22:21.642
light wave,
it bounces from one group to

00:22:21.642 --> 00:22:24.438
the other,
before coming off and getting

00:22:24.438 --> 00:22:28.528
involved in generating the
optical rotation phenomenon.

00:22:28.528 --> 00:22:31.846
But you can see,
it's sampling the chirality as

00:22:31.846 --> 00:22:34.368
it bounces from one to the
other.

00:22:34.368 --> 00:22:38.048
So if the light beam is
right-circularly polarized,

00:22:38.048 --> 00:22:42.990
that bouncing process will have
a slightly different amplitude,

00:22:42.990 --> 00:22:46.420
as we say, from if it's
left-circularly polarized.

00:22:46.420 --> 00:22:48.568
So that gives you a simple
picture.

00:22:48.568 --> 00:22:52.615
It's worth mentioning that this
is the basis of something called

00:22:52.615 --> 00:22:56.278
the "dynamic coupling model
of optical activity"

00:22:56.278 --> 00:22:59.940
that was developed by somebody
called John Kirkwood,

00:22:59.940 --> 00:23:03.588
who was chairman of this
department in the 1950s.

00:23:03.588 --> 00:23:09.557
Well now we really have to
&gt;

00:23:09.557 --> 00:23:14.690
, we have to grasp the nettle
at this point,

00:23:14.690 --> 00:23:20.895
because you just -- it's
hopeless messing around with

00:23:20.895 --> 00:23:24.000
these simple models.
 

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:25.078
&gt;
 

00:23:25.078 --> 00:23:29.509
They don't get you anywhere as
regards prediction;

00:23:29.509 --> 00:23:35.542
you know, relating structure to
sign and magnitude of optical

00:23:35.542 --> 00:23:36.650
activity.
 

00:23:36.650 --> 00:23:38.769
You have to go to the
quantum-mechanics.

00:23:38.769 --> 00:23:42.114
So now this was the expression
for the optical rotation,

00:23:42.114 --> 00:23:45.459
in terms of the refractive
index difference for left and

00:23:45.459 --> 00:23:47.710
right-circularly polarized
light.

00:23:47.710 --> 00:23:51.363
Now you can develop this using
something called

00:23:51.363 --> 00:23:54.700
quantum-mechanical perturbation
theory,

00:23:54.700 --> 00:24:00.016
and you develop an expression
for the rotation angle in terms

00:24:00.016 --> 00:24:03.650
of this incomprehensible looking
stuff.

00:24:03.650 --> 00:24:09.528
But let me just try and give
you a feel for what it's telling

00:24:09.528 --> 00:24:10.019
us.
 

00:24:10.019 --> 00:24:14.798
The heart of it is this
so-called rotational strength,

00:24:14.798 --> 00:24:19.391
which involves this so-called
scalar product of an electric

00:24:19.391 --> 00:24:23.269
dipole and a magnetic dipole
transition moment.

00:24:23.269 --> 00:24:27.165
So what we've got here is
there's the ground state of the

00:24:27.165 --> 00:24:30.087
molecule n;
j is some excited

00:24:30.087 --> 00:24:33.548
electronic state;
and μ is the electric

00:24:33.548 --> 00:24:36.772
dipole operator that's
connecting the ground to the

00:24:36.772 --> 00:24:37.868
excited state.
 

00:24:37.868 --> 00:24:41.455
And the light wave is
interacting, is coupling with

00:24:41.455 --> 00:24:45.042
this electric dipole operator,
and it's driving the

00:24:45.042 --> 00:24:46.118
transition.
 

00:24:46.118 --> 00:24:49.453
And it's this -- these electric
dipole transitions,

00:24:49.453 --> 00:24:52.990
like this, that's behind
conventional spectroscopy.

00:24:52.990 --> 00:24:57.598
You've done probably UV and
infrared spectroscopy.

00:24:57.598 --> 00:25:02.107
But now what we have in
addition is the same transition,

00:25:02.107 --> 00:25:05.470
but now brought about through
m;

00:25:05.470 --> 00:25:09.713
that's called a magnetic dipole
operator, and that's activated

00:25:09.713 --> 00:25:13.818
by this oscillating magnetic
component of the light wave.

00:25:13.818 --> 00:25:19.420
And so you have this so-called
scalar product.

00:25:19.420 --> 00:25:24.660
So μ•m,
that would be μ_xm_x +

00:25:24.660 --> 00:25:26.990
μ_ym_y + μ_zn_z.
 

00:25:26.990 --> 00:25:29.109
Some of you have probably done
vectors.

00:25:29.109 --> 00:25:30.690
Maybe others haven't.
 

00:25:30.690 --> 00:25:31.970
But okay.
 

00:25:31.970 --> 00:25:33.848
So that's the heart of it.
 

00:25:33.848 --> 00:25:36.588
But this is a very important
feature here.

00:25:36.588 --> 00:25:39.837
We're summing over all excited
states, j,

00:25:39.837 --> 00:25:41.288
all excited states.
 

00:25:41.288 --> 00:25:45.843
So the whole plethora of
excited states of a chiral

00:25:45.843 --> 00:25:49.915
molecule come in here,
and some can give you -- one

00:25:49.915 --> 00:25:53.767
particular excited state can
give you a positive contribution

00:25:53.767 --> 00:25:56.710
to the optical rotation;
another one a negative.

00:25:56.710 --> 00:25:57.618
You know?
 

00:25:57.618 --> 00:26:02.551
So it's a very subtle problem,
and you have to consider them

00:26:02.551 --> 00:26:03.890
all carefully.
 

00:26:03.890 --> 00:26:08.145
So optical activity ultimately
originates in interference

00:26:08.145 --> 00:26:12.555
between electric and magnetic
dipole transitions during the

00:26:12.555 --> 00:26:14.759
light scattering process.
 

00:26:14.759 --> 00:26:17.160
That's at the heart of it.
 

00:26:20.509 --> 00:26:23.818
Now, let me just show you how
this works out.

00:26:23.818 --> 00:26:28.053
I can now give you a chemical,
an interpretation,

00:26:28.053 --> 00:26:32.991
in terms of a real and highly
important system in organic

00:26:32.991 --> 00:26:36.519
chemistry: the carbonyl
chromophore.

00:26:36.519 --> 00:26:39.440
I believe you have come across
the carbonyl chromophore.

00:26:39.440 --> 00:26:43.269
A lot of important organic
molecules contain this carbonyl

00:26:43.269 --> 00:26:44.210
chromophore.
 

00:26:44.210 --> 00:26:49.952
It gives rise to a transition
in the near ultraviolet at about

00:26:49.952 --> 00:26:53.530
290 nanometers,
and it's widely used in

00:26:53.530 --> 00:26:56.450
physical organic chemistry.
 

00:26:56.450 --> 00:27:02.210
It's called the n to
π* transition.

00:27:02.210 --> 00:27:07.076
Now the carbonyl group itself
-- here it is -- that's not

00:27:07.076 --> 00:27:10.640
chiral, that's got a plane of
symmetry.

00:27:10.640 --> 00:27:14.348
So by itself it's not going --
there's going to be no optical

00:27:14.348 --> 00:27:15.400
activity there.
 

00:27:15.400 --> 00:27:18.546
But you see,
in this particular molecule

00:27:18.546 --> 00:27:22.741
here, 3-methylcyclohexanone,
that molecule overall is

00:27:22.741 --> 00:27:23.630
chiral.
 

00:27:23.630 --> 00:27:25.440
There's a chiral center there.
 

00:27:25.440 --> 00:27:29.795
So that carbonyl group is
experiencing a chiral

00:27:29.795 --> 00:27:32.846
perturbation,
a through space perturbation

00:27:32.846 --> 00:27:34.990
from the rest of the chiral
molecule,

00:27:34.990 --> 00:27:39.635
and that induces chirality into
the electronic transitions of

00:27:39.635 --> 00:27:43.698
the carbonyl group,
and induces optical rotation

00:27:43.698 --> 00:27:45.720
and circular dichroism.
 

00:27:45.720 --> 00:27:48.836
Well let's look at this in a
bit more detail,

00:27:48.836 --> 00:27:52.380
this famous n to
π* transition.

00:27:52.380 --> 00:27:56.472
So here we've got the
σ bonding orbital

00:27:56.472 --> 00:27:58.400
of the carbonyl group.
 

00:27:58.400 --> 00:28:03.752
There's the π bonding
orbital, made up of two -- of

00:28:03.752 --> 00:28:07.588
the pπ on carbon and
on oxygen.

00:28:07.588 --> 00:28:14.869
And here is a lone -- sorry,
here is a py orbital.

00:28:14.869 --> 00:28:17.078
So those are px orbitals.
 

00:28:17.078 --> 00:28:20.368
That's the py orbital on
the oxygen.

00:28:20.368 --> 00:28:22.949
Feed electrons in,
and so you've got,

00:28:22.949 --> 00:28:25.885
in the ground state,
you've got two there,

00:28:25.885 --> 00:28:26.890
two there.
 

00:28:26.890 --> 00:28:29.420
And you've got two electrons in
the py orbital.

00:28:29.420 --> 00:28:31.380
So those are lone-pair
electrons.

00:28:31.380 --> 00:28:36.025
So the lowest order,
the lowest transition now is

00:28:36.025 --> 00:28:40.662
the py to π*,
often called the n to

00:28:40.662 --> 00:28:41.950
π* transition.
 

00:28:41.950 --> 00:28:45.636
You're promoting one electron
from the py orbital up to

00:28:45.636 --> 00:28:51.287
the π* orbital;
and that's the origin of this

00:28:51.287 --> 00:28:52.950
transition.
 

00:28:52.950 --> 00:28:58.618
Well let's -- ah now.
 

00:28:58.618 --> 00:29:03.170
Okay, now this transition,
it happens to be fully magnetic

00:29:03.170 --> 00:29:07.798
dipole-allowed but completely
electric dipole-forbidden.

00:29:07.798 --> 00:29:13.570
What happens is electric dipole
character is induced by mixing

00:29:13.570 --> 00:29:16.099
--
well I'm giving the example of

00:29:16.099 --> 00:29:19.898
a higher oxygen dyz_
orbital into the

00:29:19.898 --> 00:29:21.618
π* orbital.
 

00:29:21.618 --> 00:29:25.411
Now Professor McBride has been
messing around with my

00:29:25.411 --> 00:29:26.869
presentation here.
 

00:29:26.869 --> 00:29:28.259
Let's see what he's done.
 

00:29:28.259 --> 00:29:35.432
So here's the n orbital,
the py orbital of the

00:29:35.432 --> 00:29:37.500
carbonyl group.
 

00:29:37.500 --> 00:29:40.309
There's the π*.
 

00:29:40.309 --> 00:29:43.640
Ah, now here we go.
 

00:29:43.640 --> 00:29:49.750
So this is now -- but wait --
yeah,

00:29:49.750 --> 00:29:52.740
so here you can see,
in that n to

00:29:52.740 --> 00:29:56.836
π* transition,
there's a net rotation of

00:29:56.836 --> 00:29:59.269
charge, a rotation of charge.
 

00:29:59.269 --> 00:30:03.778
And that's the essence of the
magnetic dipole-allowed

00:30:03.778 --> 00:30:04.818
character.
 

00:30:04.818 --> 00:30:09.190
Magnetic dipole transitions
involve a rotation of charge.

00:30:09.190 --> 00:30:12.083
Prof: And the reason we
messed about with them in this

00:30:12.083 --> 00:30:14.880
way is we've seen the mixing
p orbitals changing the

00:30:14.880 --> 00:30:17.670
orientation,
causing them to rotate that way.

00:30:17.670 --> 00:30:19.019
Prof: Right.
 

00:30:19.019 --> 00:30:24.319
So what's -- ah okay,
now here we go again.

00:30:24.319 --> 00:30:27.230
Now here's a dyz orbital.
 

00:30:27.230 --> 00:30:31.384
Now one could consider a whole
loads of other possible orbitals

00:30:31.384 --> 00:30:32.190
to mix in.
 

00:30:32.190 --> 00:30:36.144
But this is the simplest one,
just to illustrate the idea

00:30:36.144 --> 00:30:36.640
here.
 

00:30:36.640 --> 00:30:39.029
So there's a dyz orbital.
 

00:30:39.029 --> 00:30:45.890
Now going from -- you see
n to dyz,

00:30:45.890 --> 00:30:49.318
if you add those orbitals
together,

00:30:49.318 --> 00:30:57.560
you tend to get a displacement
of charge in the z

00:30:57.560 --> 00:30:59.358
direction.
 

00:30:59.358 --> 00:31:03.250
So now, you see,
you have a combination of a

00:31:03.250 --> 00:31:07.595
rotation of charge with a
displacement of charge,

00:31:07.595 --> 00:31:12.029
and rotation plus translation
gives helicity.

00:31:12.029 --> 00:31:16.480
And here we go.
 

00:31:16.480 --> 00:31:18.000
There.
 

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:23.256
So by mixing in a little bit of
this dxz orbital,

00:31:23.256 --> 00:31:28.416
you get this -- which is
electric dipole-allowed -- you

00:31:28.416 --> 00:31:32.240
get this helicity in the
transition.

00:31:35.808 --> 00:31:39.807
Now, in fact,
the rotation of charge

00:31:39.807 --> 00:31:46.205
generates a magnetic dipole
perpendicular to the plane of

00:31:46.205 --> 00:31:50.890
rotation, and it's pointing that
way.

00:31:50.890 --> 00:31:54.020
So you'll get an m_z
component, a component of the

00:31:54.020 --> 00:31:56.368
magnetic moment along the
z axis.

00:31:56.368 --> 00:31:59.375
Here you can see immediately
you've got a component of the

00:31:59.375 --> 00:32:01.588
electric dipole along the
z axis.

00:32:01.588 --> 00:32:04.923
So that generates a
μ_zm_z component,

00:32:04.923 --> 00:32:08.692
from this scalar product of
μ and m,

00:32:08.692 --> 00:32:10.940
in the rotational strength.
 

00:32:10.940 --> 00:32:17.858
So this is sort of making a
meal of it here now.

00:32:17.858 --> 00:32:20.882
So we're just putting down
these so-called

00:32:20.882 --> 00:32:23.608
quantum-mechanical matrix
elements.

00:32:23.608 --> 00:32:26.171
So here we've got n to
π*,

00:32:26.171 --> 00:32:29.830
with a little bit of that mixed
in, and that's fully magnetic

00:32:29.830 --> 00:32:30.990
dipole-allowed.
 

00:32:30.990 --> 00:32:33.509
Then we have n to
π*,

00:32:33.509 --> 00:32:36.480
which is forbidden electric
dipole,

00:32:36.480 --> 00:32:40.161
but mixing that in gives you a
little bit of electric dipole

00:32:40.161 --> 00:32:40.910
character.
 

00:32:40.910 --> 00:32:44.811
And so you now get a non-zero
contribution to the rotational

00:32:44.811 --> 00:32:45.538
strength.
 

00:32:45.538 --> 00:32:50.214
However, you wouldn't want to
go on and actually calculate the

00:32:50.214 --> 00:32:54.967
optical rotation of the carbonyl
chromophore, in some situation

00:32:54.967 --> 00:32:56.038
from this.
 

00:32:56.038 --> 00:32:58.865
Because, as I said,
there's many other excited

00:32:58.865 --> 00:33:02.130
electronic states you could have
also considered,

00:33:02.130 --> 00:33:06.403
which may be giving opposite
contributions to the rotational

00:33:06.403 --> 00:33:07.200
strength.
 

00:33:07.200 --> 00:33:12.594
You have to sum them all,
and to do that you now have to

00:33:12.594 --> 00:33:17.203
go to modern ab initio
quantum-chemistry,

00:33:17.203 --> 00:33:20.538
quantum-chemical calculations.
 

00:33:20.538 --> 00:33:25.348
There's wonderful programs out
now, from Gaussian and Dalton;

00:33:25.348 --> 00:33:29.237
you can calculate all sorts of
molecular properties,

00:33:29.237 --> 00:33:33.430
with quite good -- very good
accuracy, in many cases.

00:33:33.430 --> 00:33:37.348
But this now turns it all into
a black box procedure.

00:33:37.348 --> 00:33:42.015
You just feed in appropriate
atomic orbitals and press

00:33:42.015 --> 00:33:45.953
buttons and turn handles,
whatever you do for these

00:33:45.953 --> 00:33:50.612
calculations,
and out will pop some physical

00:33:50.612 --> 00:33:51.868
quantity.
 

00:33:51.868 --> 00:33:56.273
So you can calculate this whole
thing, ab initio,

00:33:56.273 --> 00:34:00.678
and taking in however many
excited states in the sum are

00:34:00.678 --> 00:34:01.798
necessary.
 

00:34:01.798 --> 00:34:06.152
And you can calculate the sign
and magnitude of the optical

00:34:06.152 --> 00:34:09.679
rotation, for a given absolute
configuration.

00:34:09.679 --> 00:34:13.565
So you would feed into the
calculation whether it's the

00:34:13.565 --> 00:34:17.309
S or the R
absolute stereochemistry.

00:34:17.309 --> 00:34:20.103
So you'd put that in,
and that will determine the

00:34:20.103 --> 00:34:22.780
sign of the optical rotation
that comes out.

00:34:22.780 --> 00:34:26.619
And so -- I mean,
in this particular case,

00:34:26.619 --> 00:34:28.867
this small molecule,
the S absolute

00:34:28.867 --> 00:34:31.306
configuration,
goes with the plus rotation and

00:34:31.306 --> 00:34:32.960
the R goes with the
minus.

00:34:32.960 --> 00:34:37.923
So from the calculation then
you can relate the sign of the

00:34:37.923 --> 00:34:42.289
optical rotation to the absolute
stereochemistry.

00:34:42.289 --> 00:34:45.601
But you wouldn't want to stake
your life on it,

00:34:45.601 --> 00:34:48.409
because it's not completely
reliable.

00:34:48.409 --> 00:34:52.237
It usually gives the right
answer, for smaller molecules,

00:34:52.237 --> 00:34:53.400
but not always.
 

00:34:53.400 --> 00:34:57.976
And, for example,
if this was -- as you know,

00:34:57.976 --> 00:35:03.179
and I think you'll hear more
after my talk here.

00:35:03.179 --> 00:35:09.130
Many drugs now are chiral,
and drug companies like to

00:35:09.130 --> 00:35:15.079
market now single enantiomer
versions of the drug.

00:35:15.079 --> 00:35:19.047
So it's a tremendously
important problem for them to

00:35:19.047 --> 00:35:21.476
know,
with absolute certainty,

00:35:21.476 --> 00:35:25.543
the absolute configuration of
the particular enantiomer

00:35:25.543 --> 00:35:29.115
they're marketing,
because if they make a mistake

00:35:29.115 --> 00:35:33.139
and specify the wrong absolute
configuration in their patent,

00:35:33.139 --> 00:35:36.110
they can literally lose
billions of dollars.

00:35:36.110 --> 00:35:42.375
Anyway, there's the famous --
the importance of chirality in

00:35:42.375 --> 00:35:48.110
drugs is exemplified by the
famous thalidomide case.

00:35:48.110 --> 00:35:50.420
But I won't elaborate that any
more.

00:35:50.420 --> 00:35:54.255
I think Professor McBride is
going to tell you some more of

00:35:54.255 --> 00:35:55.710
that in more detail.
 

00:35:55.710 --> 00:35:59.472
I should say that the
cornerstone, the definitive

00:35:59.472 --> 00:36:03.630
method for determining absolute
configuration has,

00:36:03.630 --> 00:36:06.278
for some years now,
been something called the

00:36:06.278 --> 00:36:09.170
Bijvoet method of anomalous
X-ray scattering,

00:36:09.170 --> 00:36:12.280
which again Professor -- have
you told them about that?

00:36:12.280 --> 00:36:12.949
Prof: Yes.
 

00:36:12.949 --> 00:36:13.619
Prof: Yeah.
 

00:36:13.619 --> 00:36:14.550
Yeah, that's the definitive
method.

00:36:14.550 --> 00:36:19.213
But it's sort of cheating
because you're actually seeing

00:36:19.213 --> 00:36:22.690
-- you're seeing it through
X-ray eyes.

00:36:22.690 --> 00:36:25.237
But even then,
you can occasionally make a

00:36:25.237 --> 00:36:25.860
mistake.
 

00:36:25.860 --> 00:36:30.436
But I should just mention also,
there are some newer optical

00:36:30.436 --> 00:36:34.860
activity techniques involving
something called vibrational

00:36:34.860 --> 00:36:36.489
optical activity.
 

00:36:36.489 --> 00:36:39.413
Here we've been looking at
optical activity in electronic

00:36:39.413 --> 00:36:41.239
transitions, using visible
light.

00:36:41.239 --> 00:36:44.949
But in recent years newer
methods, measuring optical

00:36:44.949 --> 00:36:48.949
activity in vibrational
transitions, have come along.

00:36:48.949 --> 00:36:52.231
And these are actually
comparable with X-ray,

00:36:52.231 --> 00:36:56.257
anomalous X-ray scattering,
for reliability of absolute

00:36:56.257 --> 00:36:57.599
configuration.
 

00:36:57.599 --> 00:37:00.898
That's because these
calculations are much more

00:37:00.898 --> 00:37:05.275
reliable for these vibrational
optical activity phenomena than

00:37:05.275 --> 00:37:06.710
electronic ones.
 

00:37:06.710 --> 00:37:08.179
Well that's about it.
 

